1.notes: Alternative translation of basic anthropomorphic glyph; Basic human figure representing a person or ancestor; appears in genealogical lists.

2.notes: Alternative interpretation focusing on facial aspect

3.notes: Direct anatomical reference, oval with central dot

6.notes: Updated interpretation, status: confirmed; Hand glyph used as plural or collective marker; attaches to nouns to indicate many.

8.notes: Updated interpretation, status: confirmed; Radiating circular glyph for the sun; can also denote star or light; used as celestial/temporal marker.

10.notes: Adjectival form related to moon; Crescent-shaped glyph denoting the moon or month; forms basis of lunar calendar.

20.notes: Action derived from plant symbolism; Branching glyph representing a tree or plant; marks agriculture or growth sections.

30.notes: General location concept; Rectangular or oval enclosure sign; denotes a house, dwelling, or place.

40.notes: Movement of water or liquid; Wavy line glyph representing water or sea; universal pictograph used in myths and voyages.

50.notes: Alternative stone/mineral reference; Stone or rock symbol; may denote land or foundation; used in place names.

90.notes: State of being filled or complete

152.notes: Complete entity without parts missing; Circular disk with internal markings; denotes full moon and completion; in lunar calendar.

300.notes: Female parent, birth-giver; Anthropomorphic female figure representing woman or mother; appears in genealogies.

400.notes: Descendants, children of parents; Small human figure indicating child or offspring; descendant in genealogies.

500.notes: Advanced in age or time; Distinguished human figure representing elder or ancestor; tentative.

600.notes: Specific seabird species, cultural significance; Bird glyph; the frigatebird sacred to Rapa Nui; used in creation chants and clan totems.

606.notes: Updated interpretation, status: confirmed; Composite of 600 (bird) and 6 (hand); indicates plural birds or a flock.

610.notes: Source or starting point; Oval “egg” glyph representing origin or seed; marks beginning of creation sequence.

700.notes: Updated interpretation, status: ambiguous/polysemic; Fish pictograph that can mean fish or victim/sacrifice depending on context.

710.notes: Aggressive or violent in nature; Fish with fierce teeth; denotes shark or predatory fish, ferocious quality.

750.notes: Very old or from distant past

800.notes: Flexible arm-like appendage; Octopus or tentacle glyph; denotes octopus or tentacles.

9.notes: Updated interpretation, status: proposed/high confidence; Represents sand or beach; marks Anakena beach in voyage sequence.

7.notes: Updated interpretation, status: ambiguous/polysemic; Anthropomorphic figure representing child or descendant; starts sequence of young scouts on Tablet B.

32.notes: Updated interpretation, status: proposed/high confidence; Marks divisions or section starts; used like punctuation on tablets.

999.notes: Updated interpretation, status: confirmed; Punctuation-like vertical stroke dividing verses on the Santiago Staff.

11.notes: Large marine creature symbol; interpreted as shark or seal associated with sea god Tangaroa.

12.notes: Fish pictograph; used literally and in divine names such as Ika roa.

13.notes: Symbol for cave or burial tomb; confirmed by context of scout being buried in a cave.

16.notes: Specific fish glyph identified as tuna; appears with Tangaroa as tuna incarnation.

41.notes: Variant shape not used in night count; possibly denotes day or other time unit.

44.notes: Bird glyph representing the frigatebird; used as clan totem and sacred symbol.

61.notes: Abstract sign possibly indicating darkness or female principle; color or quality determinative.

62.notes: Small circular glyph functioning as star or punctuation marker; usage rare and tentative.

64.notes: Color or quality determinative; may denote red or brightness; attaches to deity glyphs.

67.notes: Tree-like glyph representing the extinct Easter Island palm; may also signify cycle or repeat.

68.notes: Turtle pictograph; associated with god Rongo and used as name/epithet in genealogies.

69.notes: Depicts a lizard; signifies new moon or god Hiro (moko); marks beginning of lunar cycle.

72.notes: Glyph corresponding to sprout or night name Hotu; appears near dark moon period.

73.notes: Glyph representing a deity or night name Otua; anthropomorphic figure.

74.notes: Fruit glyph signifying first quarter moon.

78.notes: Night after full moon; stage of waning gibbous.

143.notes: Night before full moon; tree symbol.

280.notes: Turtle glyph; associated with god Rongo or dark moon; appears in genealogies and lunar sequence.

690.notes: Combined human-bird figure; represents the Bird-Man of Orongo ceremonies.

730.notes: Stylized shark representing sea god Tangaroa or big predator; used in genealogies.
